======================================================================
CONNECTION 3: QUASICRYSTAL DIFFRACTION (CUT-AND-PROJECT)
======================================================================

Penrose tilings / quasicrystals have diffraction patterns with
Bragg peaks at positions related to Z[П†]. Our Q_k eigenvalues
live in a similar space.

KEY REALIZATION: Q_k = |D_m(2ПЂk/p)|ВІ where D_m is the Dirichlet kernel
This IS literally a diffraction pattern: the Fourier transform of a
'slit' (interval {1,...,m}) evaluated at discrete reciprocal lattice points.

Tournament as quasicrystal:
  - Physical space: Z_p (vertices)
  - Internal space: connection set S вЉ‚ Z_p
  - Diffraction pattern: {Q_k} = Fourier intensities
  - H(T) = partition function of the quasicrystal

Comparing diffraction patterns:

  p=7:
    Interval: entropy=0.5370, participation ratio=0.4615
    Paley:    entropy=1.0986, participation ratio=1.0000

  p=11:
    Interval: entropy=0.6733, participation ratio=0.2903
    Paley:    entropy=1.6094, participation ratio=1.0000

  p=13:
    Interval: entropy=0.7088, participation ratio=0.2442
    Paley:    entropy=1.6525, participation ratio=0.7903

QUASICRYSTAL ANALOGY:
  Interval = periodic crystal (peaked diffraction, Bragg-like)
  Paley = quasicrystal (flat diffraction, many peaks)
  Uncertainty principle: peaked diffraction в†” large H
                        flat diffraction в†” small H
  This is the Wiener-Khintchine theorem applied to tournaments!

